jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F1a%2F10%2Fe72aedc64a2895fc34bc44f568bd%2Ftrantran-worcester-ma-picture.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/960x830+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F1a%2F10%2Fe72aedc64a2895fc34bc44f568bd%2Ftrantran-worcester-ma-picture.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/960x830+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F1a%2F10%2Fe72aedc64a2895fc34bc44f568bd%2Ftrantran-worcester-ma-picture.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/960x830+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F1a%2F10%2Fe72aedc64a2895fc34bc44f568bd%2Ftrantran-worcester-ma-picture.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/960x830+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F1a%2F10%2Fe72aedc64a2895fc34bc44f568bd%2Ftrantran-worcester-ma-picture.jpg" class="img" alt="Tran and her family at a Tet, or Vietnamese Lunar New Year celebration." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Tran and her family at a Tet, or Vietnamese Lunar New Year celebration.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Courtesy Tran Tran                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Alison Wong of New York City says going into the new year with a clean slate makes her feel like she can get a fresh start. "I feel like having everything cleaned allows me to enjoy the New Year celebrations."&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Setting yourself up for success&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Wong adds that many Chinese traditions around the new year, like cleaning or eating sweets, are all about setting the mood for the year ahead. "A lot of it feels about intent. [Eating] sweet treats in the morning not only signals a new change for the new year, but it's about bringing in only sweet moments in life.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-44562" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4608;         --source-height: 3456;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4608x3456+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F13%2Fd3%2F0f81e92d415dbca7695a603f47e9%2Fimg-20180128-191144046.jpg" class="img" alt="Alison Wong and her family reconnect over a hot pot meal for the Lunar New Year." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Along with a sweet treat, Alison Wong and her family enjoy hot pot for the Lunar New Year.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Courtesy Alison Wong                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;"What you do on the first day of the new year is how your year will go," said Rebe C. of Annandale, Va., "On New Year's Day, I live as if it's my 'perfect day.' I wake up early, meditate, spend quality time with family, and dedicate time to the hobby I want to focus on throughout the year.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Thao Bui of New York City and her partner believe that the first person who walks into your home sets the tone for the entire year. That's why her partner takes a walk around the neighborhood on the New Year before returning home, as part of a Vietnamese custom known as &lt;em&gt;xông đất. &lt;/em&gt;"We don't want any zodiac signs clashing with ours to bring bad luck," she said.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Lucky color red&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-44565" class="bucketwrap image small"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 2268;         --source-height: 4032;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg 200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/300/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg 300w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg 800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 168px, (min-width: 1025px) 168px, (min-width: 768px) 252px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg 200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/300/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg 300w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg 800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 168px, (min-width: 1025px) 168px, (min-width: 768px) 252px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2268x4032+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F37%2Fe7%2F6d25c6514913bce809132201cd5a%2Fdragon-decor.jpg" class="img" alt="Nguyen&amp;#039;s mother uses the lucky envelopes her daughter makes as Lunar New Year decor." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Stacy Nguyen's mother uses the lucky envelopes her daughter makes as Lunar New Year decor.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Courtesy Stacy Nguyen                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Just like Christmas and Halloween, decorations play a big part in Lunar New Year festivities. Athan Lau's family uses red decorations to sweep out bad luck from the past year. He also remembers watching red firecrackers as a kid every new year.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;"Red symbolizes happiness, luck, and celebration, all from the Legend of Nian," Lau said. "Nian was a folklore monster who ate people from a Chinese village until one day, an old man came and told the people to make loud noises, decorate their homes in red, and create bright light. Today, we dress and decorate in red and gold because it brings good fortune to our family. We also celebrate together to honor family values and our great-grandparents and ancestors who came before us."&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Eat your way to good fortune&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Many foods eaten during the Lunar New Year symbolize good luck or prosperity.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Chelsea Tan, originally from Malaysia, and Steven Teo, originally from Singapore, participate in the "prosperity toss," also known as &lt;em&gt;yee sang &lt;/em&gt;or &lt;em&gt;lo hei. &lt;/em&gt;This tradition involves tossing a salad made with fish and other crunchy vegetables.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;Tan says the ingredients in the salad represent different things: fish for abundance, vegetables for vitality and so on. Participants gather around the table and toss the salad as high as possible while shouting things for good luck. "The higher you toss, the luckier you are," Tan said.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-44558" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 5184;         --source-height: 3456;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brights