m%2Fc2%2F35%2Fef5e3c764485a49f288640714e8a%2Ffullsizerender.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2862x1609+0+450/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc2%2F35%2Fef5e3c764485a49f288640714e8a%2Ffullsizerender.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2862x1609+0+450/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc2%2F35%2Fef5e3c764485a49f288640714e8a%2Ffullsizerender.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2862x1609+0+450/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc2%2F35%2Fef5e3c764485a49f288640714e8a%2Ffullsizerender.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2862x1609+0+450/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc2%2F35%2Fef5e3c764485a49f288640714e8a%2Ffullsizerender.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2862x1609+0+450/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc2%2F35%2Fef5e3c764485a49f288640714e8a%2Ffullsizerender.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2862x1609+0+450/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc2%2F35%2Fef5e3c764485a49f288640714e8a%2Ffullsizerender.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2862x1609+0+450/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc2%2F35%2Fef5e3c764485a49f288640714e8a%2Ffullsizerender.jpg" class="img" alt="Old photo of fire captain Shane Lawlor and his two sons at a Santa Monica Fire Station. Lawlor has been a firefighter for 17 years. He was dispatched last week to the Pacific Palisades and is still fighting the fires there." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 Old photo of fire captain Shane Lawlor and his two sons at a Santa Monica Fire Station. Lawlor has been a firefighter for 17 years. He was dispatched last week to the Pacific Palisades and is still fighting the fires there.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Jaleh Lawlor                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fire Capt. Shane Lawlor was quickly dispatched to Palisades when the recent Los Angeles fires broke out.&lt;/strong&gt; He has been at work ever since. On his first day battling the flames, Lawlor was on his team's fireline for &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/01/18/nx-s1-5258948/los-angeles-wildfires-firefighter-interview" target="_blank"&gt;20 hours straight without any breaks&lt;/a&gt;. He had been sleeping on-site or at his station in Santa Monica when he was not on duty. On his first rest day from the fires, Lawlor's 11-year-old son, Cain, a budding journalist with a new podcast kit, interviewed his dad over Zoom about his experience fighting the fires. Listen to &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=nx-s1-5258948:nx-s1-5327847-1" target="_blank"&gt;what Shane had to say to his son's questions&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;25 goals for 2025&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="res1179288358" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 2044;         --source-height: 1149;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=400&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 400w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=600&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=800&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 800w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=900&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 900w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=1200&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1200w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=1600&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=1800&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1800w" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=400&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 400w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=600&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=800&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 800w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=900&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 900w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=1200&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1200w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=1600&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=1800&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1800w" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s=1100&amp;c=50&amp;f=jpeg" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2023/05/31/lk_harlan_coffee_7_wide-2d0df2898d659d07b34c2a55fc3ea425067ed7e5.jpeg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" class="img" alt="Photograph: a hand pours coffee into a mug from a glass carafe." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt;          &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;      &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Can't decide on a resolution for 2025? NPR's Life Kit has expert guides to make any goal a reality. We'll share a few of them every week this month. View all 25 guides &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/01/01/g-s1-38433/new-years-resolution" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;em&gt;here&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Caffeine is the most widely consumed psychoactive drug in the world. &lt;/strong&gt;It's in many everyday products: coffee, chocolate, energy drinks and tea. While excessive caffeine intake can lead to negative side effects such as nervousness or headaches, it also offers potential benefits; for example, coffee may reduce the risk of Parkinson's disease. To cultivate a healthy relationship with caffeine, it's essential to &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2023/03/06/1161394509/the-truth-about-caffeine" target="_blank"&gt;keep the following considerations in mind&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;☕ &lt;strong&gt;Caffeine can make you more alert or focused&lt;/strong&gt;, but you cannot use it as a substitute for food and rest.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;☕ &lt;strong&gt;Your tolerance for caffeine may vary from that of others around you.&lt;/strong&gt; Your body knows how much it needs; overdoing it can make you jittery or anxious.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;☕ &lt;strong&gt;If you want to cut back, do so slowly to set yourself up for success.&lt;/strong&gt; Quitting cold turkey can worsen withdrawal symptoms that are associated with a higher failure rate.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Life Kit&lt;/em&gt; has several more guides &lt;/strong&gt;to help you navigate your health in 2025. Check out some of them here: &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;➡️ &lt;strong&gt;Avoid these five mistakes &lt;/strong&gt;when &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/11/07/g-s1-32172/how-to-recover-from-a-bad-night-of-sleep" target="_blank"&gt;recovering from a bad night of sleep&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;➡️ &lt;strong&gt;Check out &lt;/strong&gt;this &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/10/16/g-s1-27725/comic-science-backed-mood-boosters-to-almost-instantly-snap-you-out-of-a-funk" target="_blank"&gt;comic filled with science-backed mood boosters&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;➡️ &lt;strong&gt;Here are some &lt;/strong&gt;tips to &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2018/12/12/676129459/get-started-exercising" target="_blank"&gt;help start an exercise routine&lt;/a&gt; you'll stick with.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-44220" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 5184;         --source-height: 2916;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5184x2916+0+270/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F90%2F62%2Fcc8cc45b488090b6611d090da120%2Fgettyimages-2194645034.jpg" class="img" alt="A corpse flower, affectionately named &amp;quot;Putricia,&amp;quot; goes on public display as it prepares to flower at Royal Botanic Garden Sydney on Jan. 18 in Sydney. " loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 A corpse flower, affectionately named "Putricia," goes on public display as it prepares to flower at Royal Botanic Garden Sydney on Jan. 18 in Sydney. An &lt;em&gt;amorphophallus titanum&lt;/em&gt; flower, also known as "corpse flower" (Bunga Bangkai in Bahasa Indonesia), is renowned for its foul odor reminiscent of rotting flesh.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Lisa Maree Williams/Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ol class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Staff and visitors at Australia's Royal Botanic Garden Sydney are waiting to see a rare event &lt;/strong&gt;that could happen soon: &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/01/22/nx-s1-5270914/corpse-flower-putricia-stinks-sydney-australia" target="_blank"&gt;the blooming of a "corpse flower"&lt;/a&gt; affectionately named "Putricia."&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Netflix announced it is raising subscriptions by $1, $2 and $2.50&lt;/strong&gt; per month in the U.S. This comes months after &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/01/22/g-s1-44212/netflix-price-hike-subscribers" target="_blank"&gt;the streaming service's last price hike&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The surge in bird flu, which has killed millions of hens in recent weeks, has caused egg prices to hike upwards.&lt;/strong&gt; A dozen large, Grade A eggs &lt;a href="https://www.kcur.org/news/2025-01-21/eggs-expensive-bird-flu" target="_blank"&gt;cost an average of $4.15 last month&lt;/a&gt; in the U.S. — a nearly 37% increase from a year ago. (via &lt;a href="https://www.kcur.org/" target="_blank"&gt;KCUR&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This newsletter was edited by &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/people/859721331/suzanne-nuyen"target="_blank"   &gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Suzanne Nuyen&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
