      <title>Why Netanyahu delayed an Israel-Hamas ceasefire vote. And, LA's wildfire prevention</title>
      <author>Brittney Melton</author>
      <link>https://www.npr.org/2025/01/16/g-s1-43036/up-first-newsletter-israel-hamas-ceasefire-benjamin-netanyahu-california-wildfires</link>
      <comments>https://text.npr.org/2025/01/16/g-s1-43036/up-first-newsletter-israel-hamas-ceasefire-benjamin-netanyahu-california-wildfires</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.npr.org/2025/01/16/g-s1-43036/up-first-newsletter-israel-hamas-ceasefire-benjamin-netanyahu-california-wildfires</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 16 Jan 2025 13:09:06 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div id="storytext" class="storytext storylocation linkLocation"&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Good morning. You're reading the Up First newsletter. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/newsletter/news" target="_blank"&gt;Subscribe&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; here to get it delivered to your inbox, and &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/podcasts/510318/up-first/" target="_blank"&gt;listen&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; to the Up First podcast for all the news you need to start your day.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Today's top stories&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu says a vote on the peace deal between Hamas and Israel scheduled for today will be delayed. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/01/16/nx-s1-5262339/israel-hamas-netanyahu-ceasefire" target="_blank"&gt;It's a blow to the hopes&lt;/a&gt; that an end to the fighting would take place Sunday. President Biden and Qatar's prime minister announced separately yesterday that Israel and Hamas reached a &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/01/15/g-s1-42883/ceasefire-israel-hamas-gaza-hostage-release" target="_blank"&gt;multiphase ceasefire agreement&lt;/a&gt; that commits them to end the war in Gaza. The past 15 months of conflict have killed more than 46,000 Palestinians, according to health officials in Gaza. The Israeli military says 405 soldiers have been killed in fighting since it invaded Gaza. Israelis have also remained distraught over the fate of family and friends who have been held hostage since the October 2023 attack by Hamas.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-42887" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4662;         --source-height: 2622;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/4662x2622+0+243/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F63%2Ff0%2F346aeba4429c812236726e6ac0be%2Fgettyimages-2193460782.jpg" class="img" alt="People walk past stalls selling goods amid the rubble of buildings destroyed during previous Israeli strikes, in Khan Yunis in the southern Gaza Strip on January 15, 2025." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 People walk past stalls selling goods amid the rubble of buildings destroyed during previous Israeli strikes, in Khan Yunis in the southern Gaza Strip on January 15, 2025.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Bashar Taleb/AFP via Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;The agreement starts with a pause of airstrikes and a complex prisoner exchange. Hundreds of Palestinians held in Israel would be freed and crucially needed food, fuel and medical supplies would enter Gaza&lt;/strong&gt;, NPR's Aya Batrawy tells &lt;em&gt;Up First&lt;/em&gt;. President-elect Donald Trump brought an incoming sense of urgency to complete the deal. The ceasefire agreement attempts to do a lot but leaves some questions, including: Who will govern Gaza from the Palestinian side? And how do you begin rebuilding? Ultimately, the deal doesn't guarantee long-term security for either side because it &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1224897138:1264877376" target="_blank"&gt;doesn't address a pathway to lasting peace&lt;/a&gt; and Palestinian statehood.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧&lt;strong&gt; The deal is welcome news for Palestinians, but while there is some cautious hope, some say it's too little, too late&lt;/strong&gt;, NPR's Hadeel Al-Shalchi says. Airstrikes have continued even with the announcement of the deal. The sentiment in Israel is similar. They are waiting to see the deal implemented, and there has been frustration with the government for taking so long to get to this point. Netanyahu is in a &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1224897138:1264877376" target="_blank"&gt;tricky political position when it comes to approving&lt;/a&gt; the deal, as his government might collapse because some right-wing ministers are against the agreement.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;       &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Even though Los Angeles has some of the toughest wildfire policies in the U.S.&lt;/strong&gt;, the fires currently burning are leading many to ask how prepared the region is. The &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/01/15/nx-s1-5256348/los-angeles-fires-safety-evacuation-improvement-preparation" target="_blank"&gt;county has strict building codes&lt;/a&gt; and limits new development in risky areas. &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🎧 &lt;strong&gt;The building codes for fire-prone areas in California require the use of fire-resistant materials for things like roofs and siding&lt;/strong&gt;, NPR's Lauren Sommer says. But that's only for houses built since 2008 and a majority of Los Angeles' housing stock dates back to before then. There are also strict rules about vegetation around homes in risky areas. Starting next year, almost no vegetation will be allowed within five feet of a house. The &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1224897138:1264877376" target="_blank"&gt;new rule has received some pushback&lt;/a&gt; from homeowners who like greenery outside their property.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;➡️ &lt;strong&gt;What do you do after your home is destroyed by a wildfire?&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/01/16/nx-s1-5259561/wildfire-home-survivor-recovery-tips" target="_blank"&gt;Read a survivor's advice&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Flags will be flown at full-staff for Trump's presidential inauguration&lt;/strong&gt;, despite an order from Biden to lower them to half-staff in remembrance of the late President Jimmy Carter. The flags will return to half-staff the following day. This decision follows Trump's accusation that Democrats are &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/01/15/g-s1-42957/flags-to-be-raised-for-trumps-inauguration-despite-half-staff-order-for-carters-death" target="_blank"&gt;"giddy" at the prospect of the flags not being at full height&lt;/a&gt; during his oath-taking ceremony.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Life advice&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-41616" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 5000;         --source-height: 2813;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/5000x2813+0+1246/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fe6%2Fc3%2F6294889142e084f0f83cf02da2d6%2Fgettyimages-1818577593.jpg" class="img" alt="A photographic collage that shows three hands connecting in a pre-cheer huddle, displaying the idea of teamwork and accountability. Each hand is altered to be a bright color — yellow, blue or purple — and the hands are surrounded by floating decorative geometric shapes." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 The buddy system can help you stick with your goals.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          cienpies/Getty Images                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Completing tasks that might otherwise seem challenging can be easier when you team up with another person &lt;/strong&gt;or a group to hold each other accountable. Having people to report to or work with can be a powerful tool in helping you finish tasks and achieve your objectives, says Ayelet Fishbach, a professor of behavioral science and marketing at the University of Chicago Booth School of Business. Here's &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/01/15/nx-s1-5217975/the-secret-to-doing-hard-things-and-getting-stuff-done" target="_blank"&gt;how to set up a successful partnership&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;🤝 &lt;strong&gt;Before finding an accountability partner&lt;/strong&gt;, consider the objective you need help with.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🤝 &lt;strong&gt;Your partner should have their own goals&lt;/strong&gt; to benefit the relationship mutually.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🤝 &lt;strong&gt;Pick a person &lt;/strong&gt;you can meet with consistently.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;🤝 &lt;strong&gt;You can find an accountability partner through&lt;/strong&gt; your social network, community, and online platforms.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Picture show&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-42831" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 6000;         --source-height: 3375;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1300px) 763px, (min-width: 1025px) calc(100vw - 496px), (min-width: 768px) calc(100vw - 171px), calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+0/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F60%2F98%2F9081f50c4a08b8646979b5f1fa6e%2F241206-npr-ticks-0748.jpg" class="img" alt="San Carlos Animal Control specialist Timothy Nozie and entomologist Maureen Brophy are greeted by a dog after putting a tick collar on him on Dec. 6, 2024 on the San Carlos Apache Nation. As part of an effort to reduce tick-borne illnesses, Brophy and her CDC colleagues are tackling the tick population by spraying pesticides around people’s homes and providing tick collars for dogs" loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 San Carlos Animal Control specialist Timothy Nozie and entomologist Maureen Brophy are greeted by a dog after putting a tick collar on him on Dec. 6, 2024 on the San Carlos Apache Nation. As part of an effort to reduce tick-borne illnesses, Brophy and her CDC colleagues are tackling the tick population by spraying pesticides around people's homes and providing tick collars for dogs                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Caitlin O'Hara for NPR                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever, the deadliest tick-borne disease in the U.S., has been a problem on tribal lands in the Southwest. &lt;/strong&gt;It was first identified in the late 1800s. At the San Carlos Apache Reservation, there has been a decades-long outbreak. The community-led response has reduced the number of deaths and is widely considered a public health success, especially given the resource constraints. The tribe's Department of Health and Human Services runs door-to-door campaigns a few times yearly to reduce the tick population. See photos from the community and read more about how they &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/sections/shots-health-news/2025/01/15/nx-s1-5256227/rocky-mountain-spotted-fever-ticks-dogs" target="_blank"&gt;accomplished no death due to Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever&lt;/a&gt; in at least five years.&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you go&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-42750" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 3840;         --source-height: 2160;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/flipflop/horizontal/flipflop/vertical/rotate/180/crop/3840x2160+0+395/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff7%2F6d%2F7287879f42348303a7d44d13c59f%2Fkimberly-godsey-1.JPG 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/flipflop/horizontal/flipflop/vertical/rotate/180/crop/3840x2160+0+395/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff7%2F6d%2F7287879f42348303a7d44d13c59f%2Fkimberly-godsey-1.JPG 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/flipflop/horizontal/flipflop/vertical/rotate/180/crop/3840x2160+0+395/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff7%2F6d%2F7287879f42348303a7d44d13c59f%2Fkimberly-godsey-1.JPG 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/flipflop/horizontal/flipflop/vertical/rotate/180/crop/3840x2160+0+395/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff7%2F6d%2F7287879f42348303a7d44d13c59f%2Fkimberly-godsey-1.JPG 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/flipflop/horizontal/flipflop/vertical/rotate/180/crop/3840x2160+0+395/resize/1200/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff7%2F6d%2F7287879f42348303a7d44d13c59f%2Fkimberly-godsey-1.JPG 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/flipflop/horizontal/flipflop/vertical/rotate/180/crop/3840x2160+0+395/resize/1600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Ff7%2F6d%2F7287879f42348303a7d44d13c59